    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3437199997" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3437199997" />
    <a title="Jenna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3536004-jenna"><img alt="Jenna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1535136437p2/3536004.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3437199997?book_show_action=true">Aug 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jenna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jenna" href="/user/show/3536004-jenna">Jenna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Jenna by: </span>
      <a href="/user/show/97513431-tamoghna-biswas">Tamoghna Biswas</a>
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3536004-jenna?shelf=out-of-asia">out-of-asia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3536004-jenna?shelf=classic-of-the-month">classic-of-the-month</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3536004-jenna?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3536004-jenna?shelf=historical-fic">historical-fic</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3437199997" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15321123498154033772">Once again, Goodreads proves to be the perfect place to find books. <i>Train to Pakistan</i> is a book I probably would never have learned about, or considered reading if I did, had it not been for a friend&apos;s review of this classic novel.<br/><br/>It is set during India&apos;s Partition, in a small, fictional village. For hundreds of years, Sikhs and Muslims have lived together peacefully. <br/><br/>We witness on a small scale the inter-religious hatred and violence that tore apart India in the 1940s. <br/><br/>When reading about histor</span>
  <span id="freeText15321123498154033772" style="display:none">Once again, Goodreads proves to be the perfect place to find books. <i>Train to Pakistan</i> is a book I probably would never have learned about, or considered reading if I did, had it not been for a friend's review of this classic novel.<br /><br />It is set during India's Partition, in a small, fictional village. For hundreds of years, Sikhs and Muslims have lived together peacefully. <br /><br />We witness on a small scale the inter-religious hatred and violence that tore apart India in the 1940s. <br /><br />When reading about historical events, we can sometimes forget that real people lived through them. We see them from afar and through the long lens of history. We are divorced from the personal struggles and suffering, see the tragedy on a large scale instead of from the point of view of the people.<br /><br />In <i>Train to Pakistan</i>, author Khushwant Singh takes us into the heart of the Partition. We witness history from the perspective of the individual, see how easily hatred and discord can spread. We observe how fear of the other proliferates, how easily people can be coerced to turn on their neighbours. <br /><br />Singh introduces several characters to us and writes from their various points of view. This made the story all the more real as we see these people in all their humanity, good and bad. The characters are complicated and well-fleshed out. Some you feel compassion for, others disgust at their mistreatment of others. There is an educated social reformer with false accusations against him, a young Muslim woman in love with a Sikh man, bandits, and corrupt policemen. Normal people going about their lives, thinking their small village was safe from what was happening in the rest of India.<br /><br />When a train full of corpses arrives, we see how quickly fear spreads and how quickly people can be swayed by rumors and begin to distrust people they've known their entire lives.<br /><br />This is a tragic story, dark and dismal... and yet brilliant. It is a book I will not soon forget. <br /><br /><br /><i>(August 2020 classic-of-the-month)</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="15321123498154033772" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


