    <a title="Reading_ Tam_ Ishly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/102159719-reading-tam-ishly"><img alt="Reading_ Tam_ Ishly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621043399p2/102159719.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2975333039?book_show_action=true">Sep 12, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Reading_ Tam_ Ishly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Reading_ Tam_ Ishly" href="/user/show/102159719-reading-tam-ishly">Reading_ Tam_ Ishly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2975333039" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8498434256796328641">The book is based during the summer of 1947 while the whole country was shaken with the woes of partition &amp; the riots between the Sikhs and Muslims residing at Manoj Majra, a simple village where peace used to prevail amongst the said communities.<br/>The main protagonist, Juggut Singh, was notorious in the whole village as a gangster whose days fleeted between the jail, his humble home &amp; the fields where in the name of work or laze used to secretly meet his love.<br/>*This relationship itself is a threat</span>
  <span id="freeText8498434256796328641" style="display:none">The book is based during the summer of 1947 while the whole country was shaken with the woes of partition &amp; the riots between the Sikhs and Muslims residing at Manoj Majra, a simple village where peace used to prevail amongst the said communities.<br />The main protagonist, Juggut Singh, was notorious in the whole village as a gangster whose days fleeted between the jail, his humble home &amp; the fields where in the name of work or laze used to secretly meet his love.<br />*This relationship itself is a threat to him<br />When the local moneylender got murdered one faithful night, he turned out to be the main suspect while there were valid reasons of why and why not he could be the main suspect<br />*His character is charismatically cool yet hateful<br />*He is the kind of character you would love to hate but you cannot ignore at all<br />It is the time of partition where Sikhs and Muslims were getting killed in the name of patriotism, blame games costing their lives; women getting raped and murdered; the young and old mercilessly killed in the name of the country being divided into India and Pakistan.<br />*Bodies were transferred to places where they got dumped &amp; burned<br />*There was never enough water to carry away the continuously dumped dead bodies; never enough fire to turn those bodies into ashes<br />*Arrangements were made, people made to leave homes; families were getting separated.<br />Who made the ultimate sacrifice to restore peace in such a situation?<br />✅Highlight of this story lies at the last page where the reader is hit with a jolt after a long journey of taking in all the cruelties, the deaths and separations, the corruptions and manipulations<br />👍What made the gangster stand out in the end made me really emotional<br />👎A laborious kind of read, violent scenes getting overly repeated, the slangs, too much graphic content in between the pages<br />Yet the ending &amp; the rawness of the writing style truimps in the end making me realise why it is a classic read.<br /><br />Recommended for age above 18.</span>
