    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3552915490" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3552915490" />
    <a title="Elsa Rajan Pradhananga" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/90347401-elsa-rajan-pradhananga"><img alt="Elsa Rajan Pradhananga" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1595732933p2/90347401.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3552915490?book_show_action=true">Sep 17, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elsa Rajan Pradhananga" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elsa Rajan Pradhananga" href="/user/show/90347401-elsa-rajan-pradhananga">Elsa Rajan Pradhananga</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3552915490" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11198369866408609023">The darkest period in Indian history coincided with the time India attained independence, because communal violence that broke out as a result of the partition of the country. Those on the wrong side of the Radcliffe line paid the price as rioters abducted, tortured, raped, killed and looted. Khushwant Singh&apos;s <i>Train to Pakistan</i> is a novel set in a fictional town Mano Majra where Muslims and Sikhs coexisted in peace, unaware of India&apos;s independence or partition. <br/><br/>When a train full of corpses arriv</span>
  <span id="freeText11198369866408609023" style="display:none">The darkest period in Indian history coincided with the time India attained independence, because communal violence that broke out as a result of the partition of the country. Those on the wrong side of the Radcliffe line paid the price as rioters abducted, tortured, raped, killed and looted. Khushwant Singh's <i>Train to Pakistan</i> is a novel set in a fictional town Mano Majra where Muslims and Sikhs coexisted in peace, unaware of India's independence or partition. <br /><br />When a train full of corpses arrived in Mano Majra from Lahore, the air became heavy with fear, mistrust and vengeance and the situation in the town threatened to turn as tense as was the case in much of North India. Khushwant Singh's description of the gore and violence of partition is heart rending and mind numbing. A spark was all it took for people to give into mob mentality and as mentioned in the book, ethics - the kernel of religious code was conveniently removed from their thoughts and actions.<br /><br />Khushwant Singh has managed to capture the horrors of the partition of India, the entirety of which is insane and unfathomable especially if one considers the personal struggles of those caught in the meaningless warfare. Many of his descriptions etch harrowing images in our minds. But <i>Train to Pakistan</i> is a fine classic about love, sacrifice and crime in a period of religious and political madness.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11198369866408609023" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


