<div id="review_3670209870" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3670209870" />
    <a title="Makrand" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/80273455-makrand"><img alt="Makrand" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607780211p2/80273455.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3670209870?book_show_action=true">Jan 25, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Makrand" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Makrand" href="/user/show/80273455-makrand">Makrand</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19249226-train-to-pakistan">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/80273455-makrand?shelf=indian-regional">indian-regional</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3670209870" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7721737737807895212"><b>Train To Pakistan</b> by <i>Khushwant Singh</i> is a gruesome fictional account of certain events based on real life during the historic 1947 partition.<br/><br/>In 1947 the English left however, the real problems had just started for the people of India and Pakistan who were tortured, raped and killed in the name of caste&apos;s and religion!<br/>Khushwant Singh boldly highlights the tragedies faced by the Sikh and Muslim communities by means of a fictional town of Mano Majra.<br/><br/>The book is an unbiased account of the unfortunat</span>
  <span id="freeText7721737737807895212" style="display:none"><b>Train To Pakistan</b> by <i>Khushwant Singh</i> is a gruesome fictional account of certain events based on real life during the historic 1947 partition.<br /><br />In 1947 the English left however, the real problems had just started for the people of India and Pakistan who were tortured, raped and killed in the name of caste's and religion!<br />Khushwant Singh boldly highlights the tragedies faced by the Sikh and Muslim communities by means of a fictional town of Mano Majra.<br /><br />The book is an unbiased account of the unfortunate events that took place during the partition of 1947. Since, it all starts with the train <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[and Ends with a train too (In context of the book) <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, I felt the book is aptly titled.<br /><br />The writing style greatly reflects the authors thoughts and often the highly descriptive style of writing which sometimes requires more patience on the readers end.<br /><br />All the characters in the book are going through a turmoil of their own, almost heroic at times, some fail to do what they have come for, some taking unexpected turns to do what is needed.<br />Hukum Sahib and Juggut Singh's characters clearly have been Khushwant Singh's favourites apart from secondary characters like Rahim Chacha and Meet Singh.<br /><br />The book is more about the events and the tragedies than the actual plot and hence it ends somewhat abruptly.<br /><br />Nevertheless, this is a must read to understand how lives of millions were destroyed and unfortunately no one did anything in their capacity to save those innocent lives!</span>
  <a data-text-id="7721737737807895212" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


