    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2435629108" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2435629108" />
    <a title="Zaki" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/59706402-zaki"><img alt="Zaki" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591019427p2/59706402.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2435629108?book_show_action=true">Aug 15, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Zaki" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Zaki" href="/user/show/59706402-zaki">Zaki</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59706402-zaki?shelf=2k19-reads">2k19-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59706402-zaki?shelf=english-literature">english-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59706402-zaki?shelf=personal-collection">personal-collection</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59706402-zaki?shelf=favourite">favourite</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59706402-zaki?shelf=partition">partition</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2435629108" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3043081927035698177">This novel is both beautiful and heartbreaking. Not only the narration, also the way Khushwant Singh moved the story is impressive. In just 200 pages, he has covered almost all the cultural aspects of the partition. If you have to read one small but comprehensive book on the partition, &apos;Train to Pakistan&apos; is for you. But if you want a lengthy but equally engrossing novel, you can go for &apos;This is not That Dawn&apos;.<br/><br/>Khushwant Singh is a master of cultural history. In the novel, he gives the intricate </span>
  <span id="freeText3043081927035698177" style="display:none">This novel is both beautiful and heartbreaking. Not only the narration, also the way Khushwant Singh moved the story is impressive. In just 200 pages, he has covered almost all the cultural aspects of the partition. If you have to read one small but comprehensive book on the partition, 'Train to Pakistan' is for you. But if you want a lengthy but equally engrossing novel, you can go for 'This is not That Dawn'.<br /><br />Khushwant Singh is a master of cultural history. In the novel, he gives the intricate details about the Punjabi culture. The perspectives of people belonging to the different fields of life are given a gripping way.<br /><i>"Not many people said 'thank you' in these parts."<br />"The Punjabis love people they can pity." </i><br /><br />Independence meant differently for different people. For a political party, it meant to get political positions and to get more power. For educated ones, it meant to get more government jobs and to reach to the upper echelons of power. But, for common people, it was not less than a catastrophe. They remained in the battered condition in the same way as they were living in the British era. Even now, after 72 years, one third of population in India and Pakistan is living below the poverty line.<br /><i>"Freedom must be a good thing. But what will we get out of it? Educated people like you, Babu Sahib, will get the jobs the English had. Will we get more lands or more buffaloes?"<br />"Freedom is for the educated people who fought for it. We were slaves of the English, now we will be slaves of the educated Indians---or the Pakistanis." <br />"This new government is taking very loudly of stamping out all this. After a few months in office their enthusiasm will cool and things will go on as before."</i><br /><br />Not all of them migrated willingly as a 'sacrifice', as usually told in the nationalistic histories. They were forced to leave their ancestral homes. In the villages, where majority of the population was living, they were not even aware of the new countries being carved out, new lines being drawn. In some cases, only when military came to escort them out, they suddenly came to know about those events. <br /><i>"Quite suddenly, every Sikh in Mano Majra became a stranger with an evil intent."<br />For the first time, the name Pakistan came to mean something to them---a refuge where there were no Sikhs."<br />"No one had the nerve to suggest throwing them out even purely in a Sikh gathering." </i><br /><br />At places, he also talks about the colonial mindset presistent in our daily lives. <br /><i>"The memsahibs are like houris from paradise - white and soft like silk. All we have here are black buffaloes."<br />"Even the English respect a man of religion."</i><br /><br />The character of Iqbal is very interesting. He is a foreign-educated comrade. He wants to bring change here. But he looks at everything with contempt. He doesn't realize he can't change people without understanding them. He abhors even those things which ordinary people holds sacred. All Iqbal does is talking. Even at the end it is Jugga Badmash who saves people while the comrade keeps on sleeping. <br /><br />Hukam Chand is a deputy commissioner. In the area, his commands are followed by everyone. But, a person even with such authority could be hollow inside. <br /><i>"He did not want to sleep with the girl, or make love to her, or even to kiss her on the lips and feel her body. He simply wanted her to sleep her in his lap with her head resting on his chest." </i><br /><br />Manto writes in his stories that people were more worried about trains becoming unclean with blood than spilling blood. Same scene is depicted here, <br /><i>"Why should one who enjoyed killing human beings be bothered by a stray dog getting under his wheels." </i><br /><br />The most heart-wrecking scene was when Noora was leaving the village and went to see Jugga's mother. <br /><i>"Beybey, I am going away and will never come back again. Don't be harsh to me just when I am leaving." <br />"A vague hope filled Nooran's being. She felt as if she belonged to the house and the house to her; the charpoy she sat on, the buffalo, Jugga's mother, all were hers. She would come back even if Jugga failed to turn up."</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="3043081927035698177" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

