    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3346815754" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3346815754" />
    <a title="Vartika" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/63883678-vartika"><img alt="Vartika" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1625591459p2/63883678.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3346815754?book_show_action=true">May 21, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Vartika" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Vartika" href="/user/show/63883678-vartika">Vartika</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/53449492-train-to-pakistan">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3346815754" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17357563442098051285">The Partition is undoubtedly the deepest, darkest, bloodiest wound in the collective memory of South Asia, one that displaced over 14 million people, killed 2 million, and suspended a hithertho harmonious subcontinent into mutual suspicion and hatred that permeates till this day. <br/><br/>I was 11 when I first read this book — too young, and bred too far from the horrors it speaks of, to fully understand. Yet, like every child on either side of the Radcliffe Line, I had grown up — and continued to grow u</span>
  <span id="freeText17357563442098051285" style="display:none">The Partition is undoubtedly the deepest, darkest, bloodiest wound in the collective memory of South Asia, one that displaced over 14 million people, killed 2 million, and suspended a hithertho harmonious subcontinent into mutual suspicion and hatred that permeates till this day. <br /><br />I was 11 when I first read this book — too young, and bred too far from the horrors it speaks of, to fully understand. Yet, like every child on either side of the Radcliffe Line, I had grown up — and continued to grow up — conscious and mournful of the Partition. Today, with the air full of communal hate and vitriol — and violence — yet again, I felt compelled to pick this up anew. <br /><br />Khushwant Singh's <i> Train To Pakistan </i> is perhaps the best known work about the Partition, and turned out to be a poignant, insightful reminder of what we lost — and why. The story is set in the fictional village of Mano Majra, located near a railway line next to the Sutlej on the Punjab border. The village is not only a microcosm of pre-Independence communal harmony, interdependence and friendship — a morality based on loyalty to fellow villagers — but also of the general indifference and unawareness in much of the country about the politics of Independence and the Partition. All of that is to change when a train full of corpses arrives from the other side. At the heart of it, this book explores the unbelievability of the violence of 1947: How did distrust so easily poison lifelong trust and camaraderie? How were people so driven by blood and vengeance to wipe out their own neighbours? And who is to blame?<br /><br /><i> Train to Pakistan </i> presents its answers in a subtle critique of power, as well as of morality. Throughout the novel, Singh constructs parallels between its male characters. The first of these is established by the Gunshot sequence: one night, the moneylender of the village is murdered. As the gunshot resounds, the two men in question — Jugga, a dacoit, and Hukum Chand, the divisional magistrate — tear away from the women they have been engaged with (more precisely, in the act of rape), both of whom are 16 years old. While in Jugga's case, the girl is his girlfriend Nooran, the daughter of a Muslim weaver; Hukum Chand is involved with a prostitute who, as he himself muses to himself rather guiltily, is the same age as his own daughter would have been. Is one better than the other? While the latter is a figure of authority, he remains fatalistic and amoral throughout the novel. In fact, his deliberate misdirections spark the growth of communal distrust between the people of Mano Majra. Meanwhile, Jugga lays down his life trying to prevent the rioters in the village from attacking a train full of Muslims at the end of the book. <br /><br />Another parallel is drawn between Jugga and the foreign-educated, city-bred social worker Iqbal, who are arrested and detained together. Iqbal comes to Mano Majra to educated the peasants against the exploitative capitalist class and state. He is prone to sermonising and theoretically perceptive (such as to the problem with prisons). However, despite his understanding of class and caste divisions, he does not actively oppose the privileged treatment he recieves from Jugga in custody; he does not try to mix with the villagers, is a city boy distrustful of their food and water, and maintains himself as an outsider. While a privileged character who philosophises and talks about many larger issues, such as true Freedom, he is detached from the realities faced by most people in the country. In fact, it is Jugga who bring out the more nuanced ideas in this novel, such as the colonial perception of education: he is representative of an entire mindset when he thinks of English as real education, while Urdu and Gurmukhi being mere signs of literacy. <br /><br />However, Iqbal's character is important in bringing out the author's critique of the newly-formed government in the novel. He voices the farce that the transfer of power from the British to Indians signified, remarking that freedom for the rich means the ability to rule and exercise power themselves, while for the poor it still is slavery. Throughout the book, Singh talks about the divide between the "<i> baniyas </i>" or upperclass-and-caste men in the parliament celebrating Independence and giving speeches about the country's 'tryst with destiny' and the people dying on the border. This is hardly a surprising critique coming from a Sikh man who survived the Partition violence, but it still was not as full-bodied a critique as it could be — hardly surprising, either, as Singh <i> was </i> a sycophant to later Congress governments and a supporter of the National Emergency of 1975. <br /><br />Yet, <i> Train to Pakistan </i> on the whole does see authority as a cause and enabler of the massacres — the police officers, both those under Hukum Chand and those who accompany the refugee convoys later, are seen as complicit, whether indirectly or otherwise. Surprisingly, Singh, known also for his sexism, even points fingers at the easily-threatened concepts of masculinity that pervade the Indian consciousness: when rioters enter Mano Majra, they taunt the villagers as "eunuchs" for not rising up to avenge Sikh blood, and incite them to act as a "Martial race". Again, in Singh's case it is, of course, best to see this attack exclusively in the context it's provided in. <br /><br />To his credit, Khushwant Singh does emphasise that bloodshed and terror came from both sides and both communities, without necessarily trying to equate or measure them against each other: while much of the action in <i> Train to Pakistan </i> takes place on the Indian side and is therefore threatening to Muslims, a drunk Hukum Chand towards the end is seen remembering the horrors seen by Sikhs and Hindus on the other side. He also points at the lawlessness of the age, beginning the novel with a dacoity, and also showing how refugee properties were often purposedly given to plunderers. Another mark of the time, ofcourse, can be found in Khushwant Singh's writing itself: in the fashion of all Indians writing in the English language in this period, he takes a confused stance on his usage of words from Indian languages, often replacing them with anglicised or English translations. This is often awkward — <i> sarkaar, </i> which implies lordship or an authority figure, becomes "government."<br /><br />In the end, however, <i> Train to Pakistan </i> does what it sets out to amazingly well, which is to retain the realities of the conflict that has shaped millions of lives over 7 decades now in collective and literary memory with honesty, understanding, and suitable pathos.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17357563442098051285" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

