    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_737660325" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/737660325" />
    <a title="Sumit Singla" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18177815-sumit-singla"><img alt="Sumit Singla" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1503976056p2/18177815.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/737660325?book_show_action=true">Oct 09, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sumit Singla" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sumit Singla" href="/user/show/18177815-sumit-singla">Sumit Singla</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18177815-sumit-singla?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18177815-sumit-singla?shelf=2015">2015</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18177815-sumit-singla?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer737660325" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16558907818440313311">The Partition of 1947 has probably been one of the most horrific and traumatic events that Modern India has faced. Belonging to the State of Punjab, which suffered the most due to Partition, I&apos;ve heard the bloodcurdling tales of that time from elders in the family.<br/><br/>But, none of them as gory or visceral as Khushwant Singh&apos;s narrative about it.<br/><br/>The book had been on my TBRs for a while, but what made me pick it up immediately was a train to very close to Pakistan - Amritsar. Lahore, one of the most i</span>
  <span id="freeText16558907818440313311" style="display:none">The Partition of 1947 has probably been one of the most horrific and traumatic events that Modern India has faced. Belonging to the State of Punjab, which suffered the most due to Partition, I've heard the bloodcurdling tales of that time from elders in the family.<br /><br />But, none of them as gory or visceral as Khushwant Singh's narrative about it.<br /><br />The book had been on my TBRs for a while, but what made me pick it up immediately was a train to very close to Pakistan - Amritsar. Lahore, one of the most important cities of pre-independence Punjab was only about 20 km away from where I was sitting and watching the beating retreat ceremony.<br /><br />Through the writer's eyes, I can almost see the trains overflowing with refugees pulling into stations on either side of the border and the carnage accompanying them.<br /><br />Singh's fictional Mano Majra has been spared most of the horrors of Partition and Sikhs, Muslims, and Hindus live in peace with each other. However, the coming of the 'ghost train' from Pakistan, loaded with corpses of thousands changes all that. The secular fabric of the village lies shattered among the suspicion and hatred that is fostered among its residents. <br /><br />What makes this book different and extremely powerful are the imperfections of the characters themselves. There's Hukum Chand, the indecisive magistrate, trying to bed a girl young enough to be his daughter. Meet Singh, the 'bhai' of the gurudwara, who tries but fails to talk sense into brains addled by communal hatred. Juggut 'Jugga' Singh, the ex-dacoit and ostensible murderer, with a pivotal role and probably the best understanding of honour. Iqbal Singh, who sounds like a 'comrade', with his bright ideas of equality and social justice.<br /><br />Khushwant Singh uses occasional sardonic wit and his inimitable style to narrate a story that reaches a shrieking crescendo much like the noise of the train that the story revolves around.<br /><br />What makes me terribly sad is that though this book was written in 1956, even now, nearly 60 years later, India hasn't moved on from communal tension and hatred. Watching the ceremony at the border, I realized how we're conditioned to celebrate the divide and be proud of how different/evolved/developed we are, as compared to our neighbours.<br /><br />However, I don't think we try to understand and realize that the people across the border are essentially the same, with minor variations in the language they speak or the god they worship. If only, more people understood and heeded the message in Singh's book...<br /><br /><br /><blockquote>India is constipated with a lot of humbug. Take religion. For the Hindu, it means little besides caste and cow-protection. For the Muslim, circumcision and kosher meat. For the Sikh, long hair and hatred of the Muslim. For the Christian, Hinduism with a sola topee. For the Parsi, fire-worship and feeding vultures. Ethics, which should be the kernel of a religious code, has been carefully removed. </blockquote></span>
  <a data-text-id="16558907818440313311" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


