<div id="review_2220020109" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2220020109" />
    <a title="Hesamul Haque" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/37230006-hesamul-haque"><img alt="Hesamul Haque" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1540716761p2/37230006.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2220020109?book_show_action=true">Dec 20, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hesamul Haque" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hesamul Haque" href="/user/show/37230006-hesamul-haque">Hesamul Haque</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2220020109" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16928213003683561738">Train to Pakistan is simple yet gripping and thought-provoking novel. Even though it is a fictional work, I feel there can be no doubt of stories like this to be a reality. The story is at the time of the partition of India and Pakistan but the book is far from throwing light on political disturbances, instead, it&apos;s about social understanding among the people living in a particular place. One of the three main characters, Hukum Chand, an alcoholic is drowned under the guilt of not being useful. </span>
  <span id="freeText16928213003683561738" style="display:none">Train to Pakistan is simple yet gripping and thought-provoking novel. Even though it is a fictional work, I feel there can be no doubt of stories like this to be a reality. The story is at the time of the partition of India and Pakistan but the book is far from throwing light on political disturbances, instead, it's about social understanding among the people living in a particular place. One of the three main characters, Hukum Chand, an alcoholic is drowned under the guilt of not being useful. Iqbal Singh, an educated social worker kept on dreaming as to what should be done while Juggut Singh not knowing how to read and write, did what he felt was right. He saved the train filled with Muslims passengers; one of the passengers being his lover Nooran, by sacrificing his own life. <br />Killing each other and cutting into pieces, abusing females, abducting kids. The story is such that no side can be blamed more for what's been done. The reason could be lack of education or lack of love.<br />All I can say is a quote from a famous movie, it doesn't matter what you are underneath, what you do that defines you.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16928213003683561738" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


